      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), that they were abiding in an upper-chamber in Jerusalem. What it indicates is, that their days were spent, not in the routine of common life, but in the prayer of fervent expectation; and for this no place was so fitting as the Temple, which their Master had taught them to look on as in very deed His “Father’s house,” the “house of prayer,” in which the soul of the true worshipper could find access to its God (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 20:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 2:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). There, too, we must remember all the memories of the precious days that had preceded the Passion would be with them in their fullest intensity. We find the same pattern of life presented in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 3:1",
        "children": []
